# WordPress & PHP Development Rules

## WordPress Standards
- Follow WordPress Coding Standards and naming conventions
- Use WordPress functions instead of PHP equivalents
- Use WordPress hooks system properly with appropriate priorities
- Use WordPress database functions with prepared statements

## Security Requirements
- Sanitize all user inputs, validate data types and ranges
- Use nonces for forms, check user capabilities
- Escape all outputs for display
- Never expose sensitive information in errors

## Elementor Specific PHP
- Understand legacy architecture before modifying
- Maintain backward compatibility
- Use adapters for new functionality
- Follow WordPress plugin structure with proper activation/deactivation hooks

## Performance
- Minimize database calls, use efficient queries
- Cache expensive operations
- Avoid N+1 query problems
- Use lazy loading when appropriate

## Common Patterns
```php
// Settings
get_option('elementor_' . $key, $default);

// Hooks
add_action('init', [$this, 'init']);
add_filter('the_content', [$this, 'filter_content'], 10, 1);

// Security
if (!current_user_can('edit_posts')) { wp_die(__('Insufficient permissions.')); }
if (!wp_verify_nonce($_POST['nonce'], 'elementor_action')) { wp_die(__('Security check failed.')); }

// DB
$wpdb->get_results($wpdb->prepare("SELECT * FROM {$wpdb->prefix}elementor_data WHERE post_id = %d", $post_id));
```
